{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1937122801/0353.xml":{"full_text":"BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nFOR NEXT YEAR\n(News Behind the News)\nBy PAUL MALLON\n(World Copyright. 1937. by King Features Syndicate. Ine. All Right, Reserved.\nReproduction in Full or in Part Strictly Prohibited.)\nBUSINESS prophets are as scarce around here as Santa\nClauses. Too many seers have had their whiskers\nI Binged extending their necks into the future. They (mean\ning Government Cabinet officers, authorities and econo\nmists) are currently pulling in their heads to the point of\nI wearing them inside their collars.\nFrankly their vision of 1938\nis not clear enough to warrant\nofficial public presentation of\ntheir usual rounds of rejoicing\nStatements. It is not a question\nof pessimism, or optimism,\nmerely one of eyesight.\nThose who are closest to thp\nbusiness crystal, however, can\npick out a few realistic bright\nI and dull spots which will give\nyou as careful and well balanced\na picture as they have. They see\nthese prospects for the new year:\nFirst quarter year business\nlevel will probably wabble along\non existing plane which should\nbe bottom. Expectation is based\non several factors. Prices tum\nbling downward from April to\nmid-November, have been fairly\nStationary during the last six\nweeks. They seem to have found\na basis to attract demand and\nstimulate consumption. Inven\ntories are believed to be quite\nlow. Many retail merchants\nsmartly started inventory sales\nbefore Christmas, instead of\nwaiting until the holidays are\nover.\nFurthermore, most lines are\nnow showing- a very definitely\ndeclining rate of decrease, sug\ngesting that the greater force of\ntheir drop has been spent.\nLikewise all market reactions\nlately have been slower, indi\ncating far less tension.\n\nONE adverse factor is the con\ntinued decline in farm and\nnon-farm income, for which the\nlatest private estimates may be\nnoted in the chart below. Fur\nther decline seems to be at\nhand.\nMiss Perkins\u2019 reports showed\na decrease of 570,000 workers in\nNovember. This placed factory\nemployment and payrolls below\nNovember, 1936. In addition,\nthere has been an unannounced\ndecline in non-reporting indus\ntries (agriculture, general con\nstruction and service trades)\nwhich indicates an unemploy\nment increase of 725,000 plus\nfor November.\nConservative pr i vate esti\nmates now place unemployment\n\u00bbt 7,000,000.\nSimilarly conservative esti\nmates forecast 9,000,000 by the\nend of January.\n\nMOST reasonable guess, from\nweighing all these fac\ntors, is that certainly the worst\nshould be over during the first\nhalf of 1938. Dips may cairy the\ngeneral average two or three\npoints lower early in the new\nyear but there will be a lot of\nsurprised economists in the Gov\nernment if it turns out worse\nthan that.\n\nEconomic trend of this up-an\ndown year may be traced in\nthe following chart in which all\nfigures are official (Govern-\nRetailers Plan\nNational Unit\nNEW YORK, Dec. 28. \u2014lnde\npendent retail merchants will\nmeet in New York in January to\nlay plans for organizing the in\ndependent retailers of the United\nStates on a comprehensive national\nscale, according to Leo Grizer, gen\neral secretary of the Greater New\nYork Retail Furnishings and Dry\nGoods Association, Inc., which is\ncalling the interstate conference.\nSeveral measures now before\nCongress, including the Patman\nbill, which would prohibit manu\nfacturers from selling at retail,\npropose to outlaw various trade\npractices which have long been a\nsource of grave concern to inde\npendent retailers. Enactment of\nsuch legislation, Grizer said, de\npends upon the organized sup\nport of the nation\u2019s independent\nretail merchants.\nCol. Prentiss Explains Best\nDefense Against Gas Raids\n(1.N.5.) Passive defense the\ntask of equipping whole popula\ntions against gas attacks\u2014is an\nimportant problem that must be\nsolved, Lieut. Col. Augustin M.\nPrentiss, chemical warfare expert\nof the Army, asserted today.\nWriting in the current issue of\nthe Army Ordnance, Colonel\nPrentiss said while the effective\nness of such attacks frequently is\nover estimated and the horrors\n\"grossly exaggerated.\u201d he declared\nthe problem is of sufficient\nseriousness to warrant \u201cthe united\nefforts of all the agencies of\ngovernment\u2014national, state and\nlocal \u2014to insure the people against\nthe real dangers invo'ved.\"\nCANNOT ARM ALL\n\u201cWhole populations,\u201d he said,\n\"cannot be armed to counter air\nattacks as they can to repel in\nvasions by land, but they can be\nequipped and organized to pro\ntect themselves when subjected\nTafapAoiw REpublit 1234\nI\u2014\u2014\nment except the current month,\nwhich is privately estimated:\ni g\nIJ hJ J U\nAverage. 1929 107.0 103.5 100.1 95.3 119\nAverage, 1931 85.5 58.0 87.2 73.0 81\nAverage, 1930 87.0 74.5 84.8 80.8 105\nJanuary. 1937 92 8 75.0 80 9 85.9 114\nFebruary 93.8 70.5 87.2 86.3 110\nMarch 95 3 81.5 87.9 87.8 118\nApril 96.2 89.0 88.3 88.0 118\nMay 96.8 78.0 88.8 87.4 118\nJune 96.9 84.5 88.9 87.2 114\nJuly 97.7 94.3 88.9 87.9 114\nAugust 98.2 85.0 89.0 87.5 117\nSeptember 96.8 81.0 89.4 87.4 111\nOctober 96.4 77.5 89.5 85.4 103\nNovember 93.1 73.5 89.0 83.3 90\nDec, (eat\u2019d.)... 94 2 70.2 88.6 81.5 88-9\nPROSPECTS which lie behind\nthese figures:\nNON-FARM INCOME\u2014Divi\ndends lately have been running\n10 per cent below last year, but\nbig dividends at beginning of\nyear will probably make total\ndividend payments for 1937\nabout 10 per cent above 1936.\nThere is a dearth of bonuses.\nGeneral white-collar salaries\nhave not been decreased, but\ncertainly non-farm income will\nbe lower during the next three\nmonths.\nCASH FARM INCOME\u2014 Only\nthree months ago, Washington\nexpected a farm income of\n$9,000,000,000; now the estimate\nis 8.5 billions. This cuts approxi\nmately in half the expected in\ncrease over 1936. Farm prices\naveraged 96 in April, have fallen\nto 73. Passage of the farm bill\nwithin the next 30 days will\ncarry as much assurance for\n1938 as is possible now.\nCOST OF LIVING\u2014WiII de\ncrease during the next 3 or 4\nmonths. Lower farm prices are\nfinally getting to the consumer.\nWHOLESALE PRICES \u2014Raw\nmaterials dropped from 90 in\nApril to the present 75. Prac\ntically no change in past four\nweeks, indicating that this fac\ntor which started and led the\ndownward business procession,\nmay now be stable. Prices of\nfinished products started down\nmuch later, hence their down\nward readjustment will continue.\nINDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION\n\u2014Blind spots are steel and au\ntos. Leonard Ayres has pre\ndicted autos will be down one\nthird. His is most pessimistic\nreport, considered in Washington\nas probably too pessimistic, but\na drop is certain. Autos made a\nmistake in not radically rede\nsigning cars to stimulate shrink\ning market instead of merely of\nfering better quality. Housing\nmay help steel: also expected\nexpansion of military and naval\nprograms. The industry has\nbeen scraping bottom now for\nso long the trade experts feel\nsomething must happen.\nOld House Yields\nMillion in Francs\nPARIS, Dec. 28.\u2014Gold coins\nI with an estimated value of 1,000,-\ni 000 francs and nearly 600 years\n-old have been found by masons\nI during the demolition of an old\nI house at Calais.\nThe coins are of the reign of\nr Philippe the Bold and struck\nafter April 15, 1339. As the\n5 British took possession of Calais\nsome years later\u2014l 347 \u2014it is\n5 probable that some citizen of\n1 Calais placed his wealth in a box\nin the wall of his house and died\nwithout revealing the secret.\nPart of the treasure trove will\ni go to the State and part will be\nsold to coin collectors.\nf\nHow Would You Like to Have a\nComfortable Income as Long as You\nLive for Merely Telling What You Pre\nb fer to Read? |l,?00 a Year for Life!\nContest starts Sunday, January 2d in\nthe American Weekly.\nto attack from the air. This is\nthe problem of passive defense.\n\u201c...No amount of air supe\nriority can prevent a determined\nenemy from pushing home\nattacks on cities under cover of\ndarkness.\u201d\nColonel Prentiss said while it is\npossible to provide masks and pro\ntective clothing for every in\ndividual. which is being done in\nEngland, \u201cthis does not com\npletely solve the problem.\u201d\nPURE AIR V*TAL\n\u201c...To take care of those\nsituations where individual pro\ntection cannot be employed, it\nis necessary to provide collective\nprotection, it consists essentially\nof an inclosed space, from which\nthe outside air is excluded, by\nmaintaining within the space\na slight superatmospheric\npressure, by means of purified\nair pumped in through a\nchemical filter.\u201d\nROOSEVELT MAY\nDROP PLAN TO\nELIMINATE GAO\nBusiness Protests Pour\nIn Against Program\nPresident Roosevelt may with\ndraw his plan to eliminate the\nGeneral Accounting Office in its\npresent form, according to rumors\ncurrent in political circles today.\nThis action may be taken, it was\nsaid, because of the protest of\nbusiness men in all parts of the\ncountry, against any change in the\npresent setup.\nDuring the tenure of Comptrol\nler General John McCarl, there\nwas much friction between the\nWhite House and the GAO.\nTHOUSANDS PROTEST\nThe President felt that the\nComptroller General was interfer\ning with executive powers, and\nheld the GAO was unconstitu\ntional.\nBut with the publication of the\nBrownlow report, which recom\nmended drastic changes, business\nmen by the thousands protested.\nThe GAO is the cheapest and\nbest place for business men having\ndealings with the Government to\ngo to settle disputes, they asserted,\nSAVED TIME, CASH\nInstead of having to go to the\nCourt of Claims, to secure settle\nments with the entailed legal ex\npense and long delays, they were\nable to go to the GAO and get\ndirect settlement of cases, they\ndeclared.\nAs a result of this sentiment,\nit was indicated that the Presi\ndent may change his attitude in\nthe matter.\nIred Fan Shoots\nScreen Villain\nDUQUOIN, 111., Dec. 28\u2014A\nDuquoin movie fan supplied color\nfor a \u201cWild West\u2019\u2019 picture at a\nlocal theater.\nAs the feature attraction ap\nproached the climax, the situa\ntion became too tense for one of\nthe spectators, who carried a re\nvolver in a holster at his side.\nThe fan shouted:\n\u201cDon\u2019t let him get away with\nit, boys!\u201d\nIn the next Instant the sharp\ncrack of his pistol threw two\nhundred or more theatergoers into\na panic.\n110,000 Nazi Pilots\nPrepared for War\nBERLIN, Dec. 28.\u2014Between\n80,000 and 110,000 uniformed men\nand ready to take to the air in\ndefense of Germany, foreign ob\nservers estimated today.\nBolstering that amazing air\nforce\u2014unique in view of the rela\ntively short time in which Ger\nmany has been rearming\u2014is a\ncivilian aviation corps of unknown\nstrength, a reserve group \u201con call\u2019\u2019\nfor emergency.\nPneumonia Takes\n100,000 Annually\nNEW YORK, Dec. 28\u2014Though\nmortality from the disease has\nbeen reduced 25 per cent in the\nlast 15 years, pneumonia still takes\nan annual toll of 100,000 lives in\nthe United States, according to\nstatistics made public by the\nMetropolitan Life Insurance Com\npany.\nThe company estimated that\nconsiderable further reduction\nWould be achieved when the mod\nem serum treatment is put into\nmore general use.\nNazis Clamp Down\nOn Berlin Barbers\nBERLIN, Dec. 28.\u2014German\nbarbers were warned today that\nhenceforth the use of inflammable\ncombs in the process of water\nwaving is illegal and will be\nseverely punished. Another new\nregulation is that a barber must\nwash his hands with soap and\nwater before attending each\ncustomer.\n\u25a0w\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, TUESDAY, DECEMBER 28, 1937\nBoy\u2019s Sight\\\nSafe After\nBlast\nLAUREL, Md., Dec. 28\u2014Parents\nof Robert Kraesky, 13-year-old\nLaurel (Md.) boy who Christmas\nEve lost his thumb and two fingers\nwhen a dynamite cap exploded, to\nday asked the cooperation of the\nnewspapers in warning children\nagainst \u201cplaying with things they\ndon\u2019t know anything about.\u201d\nAlthough Robert will be in bed\nfor several weeks suffering burns\nand cuts about his face and hands,\nhis parents believe it was a miracle\nthat the blast didn\u2019t blind him\npermanently. Dr. Bryan P.\nWarren today reports that the\nboy\u2019s sight will not be impaired\nand that he is on the road to re\ncovery.\nSeveral days before Christmas,\nyoung Kraesky found \u201ca little cop\nper stick\u201d while he was in the\nwoods cutting a Christmas tree.\nLast Friday evening, while the\nfamily was preparing to decorate\nthe tree, Robert started to pry off\none end of the cap with a needle.\nThe blast, which was heard sev\neral blocks away, ripped off his\nthumb and ends of two fingers.\nRobert walked into the kitchen\nand washed his injured hand be\nfore telling them what had hap\npened.\nARMAT TO TELL\nOF MOVIE IDEA\nThomas Armat, of Washington,\nwill tell how he first conceived\nthe idea of projecting motion pic\ntures on a screen, in an interview\nwith Harry R. Daniel, of the De\npartment of Commerce, on the\n\u201cStories of Industry\u201d program\nover the WABC-Columbia network\nfrom 4:30 to 5 p. m. today.\nThe dramatic story of motion\npictures from the time an English\nscientist more than 100 years ago\ndiscovered a strange optical illu\nsion in connection with moving\nobjects, will be told as well as\nArmat\u2019s first meet ing with\nThomas Edison, with whom he\nwas long associated.\nWill Hays, president of the\nMotion Picture Producers and Dis\ntributors of America, Inc., will be\non the same program. Music will\nbe furnished by the United States\nMarine Band.\nICC Favored\nGorrell Asks Airline\nControl by Board\nThe nation\u2019s airlines are still in\nfavor of the placing of air trans\nport under the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission, as recommend\ned by Senator McCarran, Col. Ed\ngar S. Gorrell, president of the Air\nTransport Association, said in a\nwire from Chicago last night.\nPrevious reports had said that\nColonel Gorrell favored an inde\npendent agency, apart from the\ncommission, to control airlines.\nColonel Gorrell, who testified in\nfavor of the McCarran bill, said\nlast night it was \u201cthe only work\nable piece of legislation yet pro\nposed for the regulation of the\neconomic phases of the airplane\nindustry.\"\nParty Planned\nBy Shrine Club\nALEXANDRIA, Va\u201e Dec. 28.\nPlans for a ladies\u2019 night pro\ngram, tentatively set for January\n6, as the first of a series of enter\ntainments to be presented within\nthe next few months by Alexan\ndria Shrine Club, were announced\nby Roger C. Sullivan, chairman\nof the committee in charge of\narrangements.\nGuest of honor at the affair will\nbe William C. Herbert, of Rich\nmond, illustrious potentate of the\norder. A feature of-the program\nwill be readings by Charles W.\nGuthrie, widely known actor, who\nplayed the part of Abie in \u201cAbie\u2019s\nIrish Rose.\u201d\nThe Broadway Playboy and His\n\u201cLending Love Library.\u201d Crowded\nOat of the Collection Like a Dis\ncarded Book, His Wife Complains In\nHer Divorce Suit, Because He Had\nOther Charming Volumes for \u201cEvery\nDay In the Year.\u201d Read About Him\nin The American Weekly, with Sun\nday\u2019s Washington Herald-Times.\nSENSATIONAL REDUCTIONS\nin The National's Pre-Inventory\nCLEARANCE!\nSave 10% to 50%\nNo Money Down! Easy Terms!\nRegular $64.95 3-Piece Living\nRoom Suite. A smart serpentine\nfront suite that includes sofa, fir 9 M Q\nclub chair and lounge chair cov- Jn\nered in durable tapestry over J\nsturdy steel spring base. Excep- Sue AT\ntional value! No Money Down!\nRegular $74 2-Piece Living Room Suite.\nThe popular London Club style with\ncarved base rails. Sofa and wing-back jK J\nchair with reversible cushions covered in UuB\ndur